1 (iv) the Secretary of Veterans and Military Families, or the
2 Secretary’s designee;
3 (v) the Director of the Maryland Park Service, or the Director’s
4 designee;
5 (vi) one county commissioner of Washington County, appointed by
6 the President of the Washington County Board of Commissioners;
7 (vii) the County Administrator of Washington County, or the County
8 Administrator’s designee;
9 (viii) the following members, appointed by the Secretary of Natural
10 Resources:
11 1. one representative of the Hagerstown–Washington
12 County Convention and Visitors Bureau;
13 2. one representative of an organization that provides
14 therapeutic services to veterans; and
15 3. the owner of land located in the Southern portion of
16 Washington County that has been proposed for transfer to the State for the purpose of
17 establishing a State park dedicated to veterans’ care; and
18 (ix) one resident from legislative district 2 in Washington County,
19 designated by a majority of the members of the Washington County Delegation to the
20 General Assembly.
21 (2) In addition to the members specified under paragraph (1) of this
22 subsection, the Secretary of Natural Resources may invite a representative of the National
23 Park Service and any other relevant stakeholders to serve as members of the Task Force.
24 (c) The Secretary of Natural Resources shall designate the chair of the Task
25 Force.
26 (d) The Department of Natural Resources shall provide staff for the Task Force.
27 (e) A member of the Task Force:
28 (1) may not receive compensation as a member of the Task Force; but
29 (2) is entitled to reimbursement for expenses under the Standard State
30 Travel Regulations, as provided in the State budget.
31 (f) The Task Force shall:

HOUSE BILL 1181 3
1 (1) study issues and estimate costs related to the establishment of a State
2 park dedicated to providing recreational opportunities and therapeutic services to veterans;
3 (2) make recommendations regarding:
4 (i) services and amenities to be provided by the park;
5 (ii) operational models for the park, including how operational and
6 maintenance responsibilities could be shared between the Maryland Park Service and
7 partner organizations;
8 (iii) options for funding the initial start–up costs of the park,
9 including infrastructure and capital costs; and
10 (iv) self–sustaining funding models for the ongoing operational costs
11 of the park; and
12 (3) develop an action plan identifying next steps for the establishment of
13 the park.
14 (g) On or before December 1, 2026, the Task Force shall report its findings and
15 recommendations to the Governor and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State
16 Government Article, the Senate Education, Energy, and the Environment Committee and
17 the House Environment and Transportation Committee.
18 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
19 1, 2025. It shall remain effective for a period of 2 years and, at the end of June 30, 2027,
20 this Act, with no further action required by the General Assembly, shall be abrogated and
21 of no further force and effect.
